                <h2>It's a me, Mario</h2>
                <p>
                    The indefinite article takes two forms. 
                    It’s the word a when it precedes a word that 
                    begins with a consonant. It’s the word an when 
                    it precedes a word that begins with a vowel. 
                    The indefinite article indicates that a noun 
                    refers to a general idea rather than a particular 
                    thing. For example, you might ask your friend, 
                    “Should I bring a gift to the party?” Your 
                    friend will understand that you are not 
                    asking about a specific type of gift or a 
                    specific item. “I am going to bring an apple pie,” 
                    your friend tells you. Again, the indefinite 
                    article indicates that she is not talking about 
                    a specific apple pie. Your friend probably 
                    doesn’t even have any pie yet. The indefinite 
                    article only appears with singular nouns. 
                </p>
            </article>
